 118 class IterOnlyRange:
 119     """User-defined iterable class which only support __iter__.
 120 
 121     It is not specified to inherit ``object``, so indexing on a instance will
 122     raise an ``AttributeError`` rather than ``TypeError`` in Python 2.
 123 
 124     >>> r = IterOnlyRange(5)
 125     >>> r[0]
 126     AttributeError: IterOnlyRange instance has no attribute '__getitem__'
 127 
 128     Note: In Python 3, ``TypeError`` will be raised because ``object`` is
 129     inherited implicitly by default.
 130 
 131     >>> r[0]
 132     TypeError: 'IterOnlyRange' object does not support indexing
 133     """
 134     def __init__(self, n):
 135         """Set the length of the range."""
 136         self.n = n
 137 
 138     def __iter__(self):
 139         """Works same as range()."""
 140         return iter(range(self.n))

 202 class PeekableTests(TestCase):
 203     """Tests for ``peekable()`` behavor not incidentally covered by testing
 204     ``collate()``
 205 
 206     """
 207     def test_peek_default(self):
 208         """Make sure passing a default into ``peek()`` works."""
 209         p = mi.peekable([])
 210         self.assertEqual(p.peek(7), 7)
 211 
 212     def test_truthiness(self):
 213         """Make sure a ``peekable`` tests true iff there are items remaining in
 214         the iterable.
 215 
 216         """
 217         p = mi.peekable([])
 218         self.assertFalse(p)
 219 
 220         p = mi.peekable(range(3))
 221         self.assertTrue(p)
 222 
 223     def test_simple_peeking(self):
 224         """Make sure ``next`` and ``peek`` advance and don't advance the
 225         iterator, respectively.
 226 
 227         """
 228         p = mi.peekable(range(10))
 229         self.assertEqual(next(p), 0)
 230         self.assertEqual(p.peek(), 1)
 231         self.assertEqual(next(p), 1)
 232 
 233     def test_indexing(self):
 234         """
 235         Indexing into the peekable shouldn't advance the iterator.
 236         """
 237         p = mi.peekable('abcdefghijkl')
 238 
 239         # The 0th index is what ``next()`` will return
 240         self.assertEqual(p[0], 'a')
 241         self.assertEqual(next(p), 'a')
 242 
 243         # Indexing further into the peekable shouldn't advance the itertor
 244         self.assertEqual(p[2], 'd')
 245         self.assertEqual(next(p), 'b')
 246 
 247         # The 0th index moves up with the iterator; the last index follows
 248         self.assertEqual(p[0], 'c')
 249         self.assertEqual(p[9], 'l')
 250 
 251         self.assertEqual(next(p), 'c')
 252         self.assertEqual(p[8], 'l')
 253 
 254         # Negative indexing should work too
 255         self.assertEqual(p[-2], 'k')
 256         self.assertEqual(p[-9], 'd')
 257         self.assertRaises(IndexError, lambda: p[-10])
 258 
 259     def test_slicing(self):
 260         """Slicing the peekable shouldn't advance the iterator."""
 261         seq = list('abcdefghijkl')
 262         p = mi.peekable(seq)
 263 
 264         # Slicing the peekable should just be like slicing a re-iterable
 265         self.assertEqual(p[1:4], seq[1:4])
 266 
 267         # Advancing the iterator moves the slices up also
 268         self.assertEqual(next(p), 'a')
 269         self.assertEqual(p[1:4], seq[1:][1:4])
 270 
 271         # Implicit starts and stop should work
 272         self.assertEqual(p[:5], seq[1:][:5])
 273         self.assertEqual(p[:], seq[1:][:])
 274 
 275         # Indexing past the end should work
 276         self.assertEqual(p[:100], seq[1:][:100])
 277 
 278         # Steps should work, including negative
 279         self.assertEqual(p[::2], seq[1:][::2])
 280         self.assertEqual(p[::-1], seq[1:][::-1])
 281 
 282     def test_slicing_reset(self):
 283         """Test slicing on a fresh iterable each time"""
 284         iterable = ['0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5']
 285         indexes = list(range(-4, len(iterable) + 4)) + [None]
 286         steps = [1, 2, 3, 4, -1, -2, -3, 4]
 287         for slice_args in product(indexes, indexes, steps):
 288             it = iter(iterable)
 289             p = mi.peekable(it)
 290             next(p)
 291             index = slice(*slice_args)
 292             actual = p[index]
 293             expected = iterable[1:][index]
 294             self.assertEqual(actual, expected, slice_args)
 295 
 296     def test_slicing_error(self):
 297         iterable = '01234567'
 298         p = mi.peekable(iter(iterable))
 299 
 300         # Prime the cache
 301         p.peek()
 302         old_cache = list(p._cache)
 303 
 304         # Illegal slice
 305         with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
 306             p[1:-1:0]
 307 
 308         # Neither the cache nor the iteration should be affected
 309         self.assertEqual(old_cache, list(p._cache))
 310         self.assertEqual(list(p), list(iterable))

 642     def test_fillvalue(self):
 643         """
 644         When sizes don't match evenly, the given fill value should be used.
 645         """
 646         iterable = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
 647 
 648         for n, kwargs, expected in [
 649             (6, {}, [(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, '!')]),  # n > len(iterable)
 650             (3, {'step': 3}, [(1, 2, 3), (4, 5, '!')]),  # using ``step``
 651         ]:

 653             self.assertEqual(actual, expected)

 659         self.assertEqual(actual, expected)

 664             list(mi.windowed([1, 2, 3, 4, 5], -1))
 665 
 666     def test_step(self):
 667         """The window should advance by the number of steps provided"""
 668         iterable = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
 669         for n, step, expected in [
 670             (3, 2, [(1, 2, 3), (3, 4, 5), (5, 6, 7)]),  # n > step
 671             (3, 3, [(1, 2, 3), (4, 5, 6), (7, None, None)]),  # n == step
 672             (3, 4, [(1, 2, 3), (5, 6, 7)]),  # line up nicely
 673             (3, 5, [(1, 2, 3), (6, 7, None)]),  # off by one
 674             (3, 6, [(1, 2, 3), (7, None, None)]),  # off by two
 675             (3, 7, [(1, 2, 3)]),  # step past the end
 676             (7, 8, [(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7)]),  # step > len(iterable)
 677         ]:
 678             actual = list(mi.windowed(iterable, n, step=step))
 679             self.assertEqual(actual, expected)
 680 
 681         # Step must be greater than or equal to 1
 682         with self.assertRaises(ValueError):
 683             list(mi.windowed(iterable, 3, step=0))

 745         self.assertIn(10, D)
 746         self.assertNotIn(40, D)
 747         self.assertIn(20, D)
 748         self.assertNotIn(21, D)
 749 
 750         # Checking in-ness shouldn't advance the iterator
 751         self.assertEqual(next(D[10]), 10)

 753     def test_validator(self):

 755         key = lambda x: int(str(x)[0])  # First digit of each number
 756         validator = lambda x: 0 < x < 10  # No leading zeros
 757         D = mi.bucket(iterable, key, validator=validator)
 758         self.assertEqual(mi.take(3, D[1]), [1, 10, 11])
 759         self.assertNotIn(0, D)  # Non-valid entries don't return True
 760         self.assertNotIn(0, D._cache)  # Don't store non-valid entries
